## Verdict

Do **not** install Matt Pocock’s full skill pack globally for either Claude or Codex in this harness.

The stable pack is not merely “TypeScript prompts”; most of its core engineering advice is stack-agnostic and thoughtfully written. But it assumes an interactive, privileged app-development agent that can shape requirements, edit agent instructions, operate the issue tracker, implement, review, and commit. That directly conflicts with this harness’s separation of orchestration, isolated execution, fail-closed gates, and tool-denied review.

The right move is to **adapt a small, pinned subset into first-party, lane-specific guidance**. No upstream-managed plugin, no `npx ...@latest`, and no third-party skills in worker or reviewer contexts.

No installation or repository mutation was performed.

## What Matt has published

The canonical source is [`mattpocock/skills`](https://github.com/mattpocock/skills), also presented through his [AI Hero catalog](https://www.aihero.dev/skills-catalog).

### Shipping artifacts

The current Claude plugin manifest exposes 22 stable skills:

- Engineering: `ask-matt`, `code-review`, `codebase-design`, `diagnosing-bugs`, `domain-modeling`, `grill-with-docs`, `implement`, `improve-codebase-architecture`, `prototype`, `research`, `resolving-merge-conflicts`, `setup-matt-pocock-skills`, `tdd`, `to-spec`, `to-tickets`, `triage`, `wayfinder`.
- Productivity: `grill-me`, `grilling`, `handoff`, `teach`, `writing-great-skills`.

The exact authoritative list is in the [plugin manifest](https://github.com/mattpocock/skills/blob/main/.claude-plugin/plugin.json); the repository also classifies them as 13 explicitly user-invoked and nine model-invokable skills in its [engineering](https://github.com/mattpocock/skills/tree/main/skills/engineering) and [productivity](https://github.com/mattpocock/skills/tree/main/skills/productivity) indexes.

There are another 17 published directories that do not ship in the plugin:

- Seven explicitly unstable experiments: `claude-handoff`, `loop-me`, `setup-ts-deep-modules`, `wizard`, `writing-beats`, `writing-fragments`, `writing-shape`. Upstream says these may have rough edges, breaking changes, or be abandoned. [In-progress tree](https://github.com/mattpocock/skills/tree/main/skills/in-progress)
- Four rarely used miscellaneous skills: `git-guardrails-claude-code`, `migrate-to-shoehorn`, `scaffold-exercises`, `setup-pre-commit`. [Misc tree](https://github.com/mattpocock/skills/tree/main/skills/misc)
- Two setup-specific personal skills: `edit-article`, `obsidian-vault`. [Personal tree](https://github.com/mattpocock/skills/tree/main/skills/personal)
- Four deprecated skills: `design-an-interface`, `qa`, `request-refactor-plan`, `ubiquitous-language`. [Deprecated tree](https://github.com/mattpocock/skills/tree/main/skills/deprecated)

### Format and distribution

These are Agent Skills: directories containing a YAML-frontmatter `SKILL.md`, sometimes with referenced Markdown, templates, scripts, assets, and Codex metadata. That matches the [Open Agent Skills format](https://openagentskills.dev/docs/specification).

Distribution paths are:

- `npx skills@latest add mattpocock/skills`, copying skills into Claude, Codex, or other compatible agent directories.
- A native Claude Code marketplace/plugin named `mattpocock-skills@mattpocock`. [Upstream installation documentation](https://github.com/mattpocock/skills#quickstart-30-second-setup)
- The plugin’s [marketplace manifest](https://github.com/mattpocock/skills/blob/main/.claude-plugin/marketplace.json) points at the repository itself.

This is **not an MCP package**. The current plugin manifest declares only skills—no MCP servers, hooks, agents, or LSP servers. Some skills nevertheless instruct the host agent to run shell/git/`gh`, mutate issue trackers, edit files, spawn agents, or commit.

License is [MIT, copyright Matt Pocock 2026](https://github.com/mattpocock/skills/blob/main/LICENSE), so internal adaptation is legally straightforward with attribution and license retention.

### Maintenance state

It is actively maintained but moving quickly:

- GitHub showed 307 commits, with multiple substantive commits through July 10, 2026. [Commit history](https://github.com/mattpocock/skills/commits/main/)
- Latest published release was [v1.1.0 on July 8, 2026](https://github.com/mattpocock/skills/releases/tag/v1.1.0).
- `main` already declares plugin version 1.2.0 while [`package.json`](https://raw.githubusercontent.com/mattpocock/skills/main/package.json) still says 1.1.0. That means moving `main` is ahead of the latest release, not a stable audited target.
- The visible Actions directory contains only a release workflow; I found no published behavioral eval or validation CI. [Workflow directory](https://github.com/mattpocock/skills/tree/main/.github/workflows)

So: healthy maintenance, high churn, and no strong public evidence that the prompts have been evaluated across Python/bash trust-oriented harnesses.

## Content quality and harness fit

The editorial quality is generally high:

- `grilling` cleanly separates discoverable facts from human decisions and adds an explicit confirmation gate. [Source](https://raw.githubusercontent.com/mattpocock/skills/main/skills/productivity/grilling/SKILL.md)
- `tdd` emphasizes public interfaces, independently derived expectations, and vertical red-green slices. [Source](https://raw.githubusercontent.com/mattpocock/skills/main/skills/engineering/tdd/SKILL.md)
- `diagnosing-bugs` builds a reproducible feedback loop before theorizing, then minimizes, ranks falsifiable hypotheses, instruments, fixes, and regression-tests. [Source](https://raw.githubusercontent.com/mattpocock/skills/main/skills/engineering/diagnosing-bugs/SKILL.md)
- `code-review` deliberately separates standards compliance from spec fidelity. [Source](https://raw.githubusercontent.com/mattpocock/skills/main/skills/engineering/code-review/SKILL.md)
- `writing-great-skills` has unusually good material on invocation, context load, progressive disclosure, completion criteria, and prompt sediment. [Source](https://raw.githubusercontent.com/mattpocock/skills/main/skills/productivity/writing-great-skills/SKILL.md)

But several rules are opinionated rather than universal: no refactoring during red-green, “one adapter means a hypothetical seam,” forcing exact architectural vocabulary, and “always resolve; never abort” during merge conflicts. Those should not silently outrank approved specs or operator policy.

The stable pack is **not mostly TypeScript-only**. The more accurate criticism is: it is mostly built for interactive application development. TypeScript appears in examples, `to-tickets` assumes schema/API/UI vertical slices, and several non-shipping skills are explicitly TS/Husky/Prettier-oriented. The harness mismatch is primarily authority and workflow, not language.

## Supply-chain assessment

Skills are executable policy in prose. Their metadata is placed in agent context, and their complete instructions load when invoked; supporting scripts may then be executed. Claude’s own documentation warns that project skills can grant broad tool access and should be reviewed before workspace trust is accepted. [Claude Code skills documentation](https://code.claude.com/docs/en/slash-commands)

The upstream pack currently looks benign, but the trust question is not “Is Matt malicious?” It is:

- Can a future upstream change alter high-privilege agent behavior?
- Can an auto-invoked skill override the harness’s role boundaries?
- Does installation add a second, unreviewed orchestration system?
- Can reviewer independence be contaminated even when tools are denied?

The answer to all four is yes.

The full pack includes instructions to:

- Edit `CLAUDE.md` or `AGENTS.md` and create agent configuration files. [`setup-matt-pocock-skills`](https://raw.githubusercontent.com/mattpocock/skills/main/skills/engineering/setup-matt-pocock-skills/SKILL.md)
- Create, label, assign, comment on, and close issues. [`triage`](https://raw.githubusercontent.com/mattpocock/skills/main/skills/engineering/triage/SKILL.md)
- Publish specs and tickets directly to trackers. [`to-spec`](https://raw.githubusercontent.com/mattpocock/skills/main/skills/engineering/to-spec/SKILL.md), [`to-tickets`](https://raw.githubusercontent.com/mattpocock/skills/main/skills/engineering/to-tickets/SKILL.md)
- Implement, review, and commit on the current branch. [`implement`](https://raw.githubusercontent.com/mattpocock/skills/main/skills/engineering/implement/SKILL.md)
- Resolve and finish merges/rebases without aborting. [`resolving-merge-conflicts`](https://raw.githubusercontent.com/mattpocock/skills/main/skills/engineering/resolving-merge-conflicts/SKILL.md)
- Spawn parallel or background agents. [`code-review`](https://raw.githubusercontent.com/mattpocock/skills/main/skills/engineering/code-review/SKILL.md), [`research`](https://raw.githubusercontent.com/mattpocock/skills/main/skills/engineering/research/SKILL.md)

Worker isolation protects credentials and the operator’s home. It does **not** protect patch integrity: a tainted worker instruction can still produce in-scope-looking but semantically wrong code. Gates help detect that; they should not be treated as permission to feed workers untrusted policy.

Likewise, a tool-denied reviewer cannot mutate state, but injected review instructions can still bias its verdict or cause it to apply a generic Fowler baseline instead of the approved bounded-review rubric.

Anthropic recommends reviewing commands and critical-file changes and using isolation around untrusted scripts. [Claude security guidance](https://code.claude.com/docs/en/security) Independent security research specifically recommends internally vetted skill sources and an approval process. [Reversec analysis](https://labs.reversec.com/posts/2026/05/skill-issues-compromising-claude-code-with-malicious-skills-agents-part-1)

### Tolerable contexts

| Context | Third-party skill tolerance |
|---|---|
| Claude orchestrator | Only tiny, audited, pinned, explicitly invoked adaptations. High privilege makes a managed bundle inappropriate. |
| Codex planner | Read-only/advisory adaptations are acceptable if first-party and harness-specific. |
| Codex worker/executor | No general third-party pack. Only sanitized first-party instructions incorporated into the worker contract. |
| Reviewer | None. Preserve a minimal, hermetic, harness-owned review prompt. Tool denial does not prevent semantic contamination. |
| SOL consult | Most tolerant because it is read-only, but prefer task-supplied guidance over persistent/global installation. |

## Per-skill recommendations

“Adapt” below means copy the useful ideas into an internally owned, pinned skill or prompt—not install upstream.

| Skill or pack | Claude | Codex | Reason |
|---|---|---|---|
| `grilling` | **Adapt** for explicit pre-spec operator use | **Adapt** for planner/consult only | Excellent requirements shaping; remove “relentless” excess and keep it outside workers/reviewers. |
| `grill-me`, `grill-with-docs` | **Skip wrappers** | **Skip wrappers** | `grill-with-docs` pulls in inline `CONTEXT.md`/ADR writes; the core loop is enough. |
| `domain-modeling` | **Adapt read-only** | **Adapt for planner/consult** | Useful vocabulary checks, but propose glossary/ADR changes through the normal approval path instead of writing inline. |
| `codebase-design` | **Adapt selectively** | **Adapt for planner/consult** | Deep-module/seam/locality concepts are useful and stack-agnostic; remove mandatory vocabulary and TS examples. |
| `tdd` | **Skip for Claude runtime** | **Adapt for approved executor specs** | Retain behavior-level tests and vertical slices; approved `test_command`, scope, and immutable spec must win. |
| `diagnosing-bugs` | **Skip generally** | **Adapt only for bug-specific jobs** | Strong debugging loop, but prototypes, instrumentation, test creation, and bisection must be explicitly in scope. |
| `research` | **Skip as a skill** | **Adapt into consult policy** | Primary-source/citation discipline fits SOL; background-agent spawning and repo writes do not. |
| `code-review` | **Skip** | **Skip** | Duplicates and conflicts with integrity → scope → test → bounded review; it also assumes git/tool/sub-agent access. |
| `ask-matt`, `setup-matt-pocock-skills` | **Skip** | **Skip** | Introduces a competing workflow router and edits authoritative agent instructions. |
| `triage`, `to-spec`, `to-tickets`, `wayfinder`, `implement` | **Skip** | **Skip** | Bypasses schema-validated immutable specs, approval artifacts, dispatcher isolation, branch conventions, and gates. |
| `prototype`, `improve-codebase-architecture` | **Skip** | **Skip runtime**; concepts may inform consults | They create code/reports/branches and encourage opportunistic work outside approved specs. |
| `resolving-merge-conflicts` | **Skip** | **Skip** | “Always resolve; never abort” is incompatible with operator-only promotion and fail-closed handling. |
| `handoff` | **Skip** | **Skip** | Harness evidence, manifests, logs, and recoverable JSON answers already provide controlled handoff. |
| `teach` | **Skip** | **Skip** | No meaningful harness relevance. |
| `writing-great-skills` | **Adapt as maintainer reference** | **Skip runtime** | Valuable when designing first-party skills, but unnecessary in production agent contexts. |
| All experimental/misc/personal/deprecated skills | **Skip** | **Skip** | Explicitly unstable, personal, TS-specific, rare-use, or deprecated. |

## Recommended adoption pattern

If the operator wants to proceed, create a small first-party “harness reasoning” set derived from only:

1. `grilling` for pre-approval requirements shaping.
2. Selected `domain-modeling` and `codebase-design` concepts for planner/consult.
3. A constrained TDD/debugging checklist for explicitly authorized Codex worker jobs.
4. Primary-source/citation rules for SOL consults.

For each adaptation:

- Vendor the reviewed text at an exact upstream commit SHA.
- Record origin, SHA, retrieval date, MIT notice, internal owner, and content digest.
- Make every skill explicitly invoked; disable model invocation.
- Remove bundled scripts, issue-tracker actions, git commits, sub-agent spawning, and writes to `AGENTS.md`/`CLAUDE.md`.
- State precedence explicitly: approved spec, schema, dispatcher contract, and harness gates override the skill.
- Never load it into reviewer context.
- Update only through a normal reviewed change, not upstream auto-update.

So the plain answer is: **good material, low direct fit; adapt about four narrow ideas, install none of the pack for either Claude or Codex.**

Review-basis note: `AGENTS.md` was supplied verbatim in the request. Local shell access to `CLAUDE.md` failed at the environment’s `bwrap` namespace setup before file access, so I relied on the Claude/orchestrator, Codex planner/executor, reviewer-denial, and trust-boundary facts explicitly supplied by the operator rather than claiming an unread local file was inspected.

